    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_938807510" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/938807510" />
    <a title="Agnieszka" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2446508-agnieszka"><img alt="Agnieszka" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1371835955p2/2446508.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/938807510?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Agnieszka" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Agnieszka" href="/user/show/2446508-agnieszka">Agnieszka</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780349004600" href="/book/show/24568234-the-paying-guests">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2446508-agnieszka?shelf=read-more-women">read-more-women</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2446508-agnieszka?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2446508-agnieszka?shelf=2015">2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2446508-agnieszka?shelf=own-a-copy">own-a-copy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2446508-agnieszka?shelf=sarah-waters">sarah-waters</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer938807510" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15366725749773916465"><br/>It is year 1922, the dust after the turmoil of war hardly fell, the higher social classes have lost their fortunes and former status and are forced to live in new circumstances. Such fate shares 26-year-old Frances Wray who lives with her mother in decaying house in the suburbs of London. Her brothers died at the front and father died leaving family in debts. Frances, formerly feisty activist and suffragist all at once has a lot on her plate. She’s a maid and gardener, cleaning lady and nurse. H</span>
  <span id="freeText15366725749773916465" style="display:none"><br />It is year 1922, the dust after the turmoil of war hardly fell, the higher social classes have lost their fortunes and former status and are forced to live in new circumstances. Such fate shares 26-year-old Frances Wray who lives with her mother in decaying house in the suburbs of London. Her brothers died at the front and father died leaving family in debts. Frances, formerly feisty activist and suffragist all at once has a lot on her plate. She’s a maid and gardener, cleaning lady and nurse. Her days go on scrubbing floors, dusting, cleaning, cooking and caring about a bit neurotic and overbearing mother. And horror of horrors !, in mother’s eyes and sometimes in her own too she is at risk of spinsterhood.<br /><br />To make ends meet Frances has to rent rooms and take lodgers, young couple, Lily and Leonard Barber, <i> two walking shillings </i>. And from that moment nothing would be the same. This is a starting point for <i> Paying guests </i>.<br /> <br />Writing, set in victorian England <i> Fingersmith </i> Sarah Waters recklessly broke into literary Parnassus. And set herself the bar really high. Her latest novel doesn't dissapoint, it's precisely constructed tale that little by little transforms from the novel of manners into romance, from romance into thriller. To finally become a deep psychological drama. <br /><br />The story unfolds rather slowly, we get an accurate descriptions of post-war England, this world when men having returned from the war could not quite pull themselves together while women slowly began to gain more and more space and social consciousness. I found both psychological portraits of the protagonists and their life choices, courage and moral dilemmas very well written.<br /><br />At some point however, lulled a bit with some of these mundane aspects, all of a sudden we find themselves in the middle of a forbidden romance. I'm not going to reveal more to not spoil anyone’s reading. I can recommend this one and though this is not <i> Fingersmith </i> it’s still really good and engrossing piece of writing.<br /><br />3,5/5</span>
  <a data-text-id="15366725749773916465" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


